{"item_id": "case:vllm@a5e9d511defe", "kind": "case", "repo": "vllm", "findings": [{"severity": "important", "category": "gpu-precision/fp64-in-hot-kernel", "claim": "The Gumbel sampling kernel (`_gumbel_sample_kernel`) was changed to convert logits to FP64 unconditionally (`logits = logits.to(tl.float64)`) and now performs the full per-token vocab max-reduction (`tl.max` over the entire vocab, ~128K elements in BLOCK_SIZE=1024 chunks) plus gumbel-noise math in FP64, and the `local_max` output tensor is now allocated as torch.float64. This kernel is the core token-sampling routine invoked via `Sampler.sample` -> `gumbel_sample` on EVERY decode step for EVERY request (plus in eagle speculator and residual resampling in rejection_sampler), i.e., a per-step hot path. On most GPUs FP64 arithmetic runs at a small fraction of FP32 throughput (typically 1/32-1/64 on consumer/Ada/Hopper-consumer parts, 1/2 on A100/H100 datacenter), so making the whole-vocab reduction FP64 can substantially slow sampling and increase per-step latency. Note the FP64 cast and FP64 max-reduction run even for greedy sampling (temp==0), where the expensive FP64 gumbel noise is not even used, so the greedy path also pays the cost. This is default-enabled (no opt-in flag). Prior commit history (5fcb0cdd6 'Use FP32 for Gumbel Noise') shows the precision of this kernel is a known perf-sensitive tradeoff.", "confidence": 0.72, "hot_path": true, "default_enabled": true, "file": "vllm/v1/worker/gpu/sample/gumbel.py", "leaf": "gpu-precision/fp64-arithmetic-in-hot-path"}, {"severity": "suggestion", "category": "gpu-precision/fp64-in-hot-kernel", "claim": "In `_probabilistic_rejection_kernel`, target_prob/draft_prob loads and the uniform sample now use FP64 (`.to(tl.float64)` and `tl_rand64`). This path is only reached when `use_strict_rejection_sampling=False` (opt-in probabilistic rejection sampling for spec decode) and only does a handful of scalar FP64 ops per accepted draft token, so the perf impact is negligible compared to the gumbel kernel; reporting only for completeness.", "confidence": 0.4, "hot_path": false, "default_enabled": false, "file": "vllm/v1/worker/gpu/spec_decode/rejection_sampler.py", "leaf": "gpu-precision/fp64-arithmetic-in-hot-path"}], "leak_attempt": false, "latency_s": 38.71, "n_turns": 1, "cost": 0.3430125, "gate": false, "decomposed": false, "n_groups": 1, "scenario": null, "tokens": {"in": 0, "out": 0}}
{"item_id": "case:vllm@f09daea261ee", "kind": "case", "repo": "vllm", "findings": [{"severity": "important", "category": "cpu-hotpath-debug-io", "claim": "process_weights_after_loading() in CPUAWQLinearMethod unconditionally calls torch.set_printoptions(profile=\"full\", linewidth=5000, sci_mode=False). This is a leftover debug statement. While process_weights_after_loading is a one-time cold path (per layer, at load), it mutates a GLOBAL torch print setting to 'full' profile with 5000 linewidth. Any later code path that prints/logs a tensor (e.g. debug logging, error messages, repr of tensors) will now dump entire tensors uncompressed, which can be extremely slow and produce huge output. This is a global side-effect that leaks out of the CPU AWQ path and is enabled by default whenever a CPU AWQ model loads.", "confidence": 0.55, "file": "vllm/model_executor/layers/quantization/cpu_wna16.py", "hot_path": false, "default_enabled": true, "leaf": "leftover-debug-global-state"}, {"severity": "important", "category": "cpu-quant-debug-artifact", "claim": "In CPUAWQLinearMethod.process_weights_after_loading, a debug statement `torch.set_printoptions(profile=\"full\", linewidth=5000, sci_mode=False)` is present. While weight processing is a one-time (cold path) operation and not per-step, this call globally mutates torch print options as a side effect — a leftover debug artifact. It does not itself add per-inference overhead (called once per layer at load), so it is not a runtime hot-path regression. Flagging as a low-severity hygiene issue rather than a perf regression. NOTE: this line is present in the parent snapshot; the commit's diff shown only touches cmake, so this is pre-existing, not introduced here.", "confidence": 0.4, "file": "vllm/model_executor/layers/quantization/cpu_wna16.py", "hot_path": false, "default_enabled": true, "leaf": null}], "leak_attempt": false, "latency_s": 43.13, "n_turns": 5, "cost": 0.638685, "gate": false, "decomposed": true, "n_groups": 5,