{"item_id": "case:vllm@6ae8bbd0c2fa", "kind": "case", "repo": "vllm", "findings": [{"severity": "important", "category": "cudagraph/graph-capture-disabled", "claim": "On XPU, this commit changes the default so that cudagraph_mode is forced to CUDAGraphMode.NONE unless VLLM_XPU_ENABLE_XPU_GRAPH=1 is set. Previously (parent), when supports_xpu_graph() was true and world_size_across_dp<=1, the default path fell back to CUDAGraphMode.PIECEWISE (XPU graph enabled) for FLASH_ATTN. The new `elif not envs.VLLM_XPU_ENABLE_XPU_GRAPH` branch unconditionally disables all cudagraph capture in the default configuration. While the flip happens in check_and_update_config (a one-time init/cold path called once from VllmConfig setup, vllm/config/vllm.py:1084), its effect is on the hot decode path: with cudagraph disabled, every decode step executes eagerly instead of replaying a captured graph, adding per-step Python/launch overhead and reducing decode throughput on Intel GPUs. This is enabled by default (opt-out via env var), so out-of-the-box XPU users see the eager-mode regression. Note the change appears intentional (likely for stability/correctness), but from a pure runtime-performance standpoint it is a default-config throughput regression.", "confidence": 0.7, "hot_path": true, "default_enabled": true, "file": "vllm/platforms/xpu.py", "leaf": "cudagraph/graph-capture-disabled"}], "leak_attempt": false, "latency_s": 22.33, "n_turns": 1, "cost": 0.09614725, "gate": false, "decomposed": false, "n_groups": 1, "scenario": null, "tokens": {"in": 0, "out": 0}}
